---

<DecisionGuideLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  hubSlug="sauna-kits"
  heroSubtitle={heroSubtitle}
  image="/images/heroes/sauna-kits.webp"
  imageAlt="A partly built sauna showing cedar cladding over a foil vapor barrier and framing."
  pubDate={pubDate}
  updatedDate={updatedDate}
  lastReviewed={lastReviewed}
  methodologyNote={methodologyNote}
  sources={sources}
  faq={faq}
  heroGuides={heroGuides}
>
  <p>
    Building your own sauna is the best value per square foot - especially for larger or custom
    rooms - if you are comfortable with framing, insulation, a vapor barrier, and finish carpentry.
    The decision is not which kit "wins": it is <strong>kit vs scratch build</strong>, the right
    <strong>heater kW for your room's volume</strong>, and the <strong>240V circuit</strong> that
    heater demands. Get those three right and the rest is execution.
  </p>
  <p>
    Below we walk the build step by step, give you heater-sizing and circuit tables you can plan
    against, shortlist the heaters worth considering, and cover the woods and details beginners get
    wrong. For a full itemized budget, run the
    <a href="/tools/sauna-cost-calculator/">sauna cost calculator</a>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="steps">Build a sauna step by step</h2>
  <p>
    Every build comes down to the same ordered decisions. Expand each step for the detail - the order
    matters, because your size choice drives the heater, and the heater drives the electrical.
  </p>

  <div class="build-steps not-prose">
    {
      buildSteps.map((step) => (
        <details class="build-step">
          <summary class="build-step__summary">
            <span class="build-step__num">{step.n}</span>
            <span class="build-step__title">{step.title}</span>
            <span class="build-step__chevron" aria-hidden="true" />
          </summary>
          <div class="build-step__body" set:html={step.body} />
        </details>
      ))
    }
  </div>

  <h2 id="approach">Kit vs scratch build vs room conversion</h2>
  <p>
    There are three realistic DIY paths. Most people are best served by a pre-cut kit plus a
    separately chosen quality heater.
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable
    caption="DIY sauna build approaches compared by skill, time, cost, and best fit"
    headers={["Approach", "Skill needed", "Time", "Typical cost", "Best for"]}
    rows={approachRows}
  />

  <Callout variant="note" title="Kits remove the hardest work">
    <p>
      A pre-cut kit ships pre-measured wall and bench components, a vapor barrier, and a heater spec,
      so you skip the most error-prone cutting and fitting. Scratch-building costs less in materials
      but assumes you can detail the vapor barrier and ventilation correctly - the part beginners
      most often get wrong and the most expensive to fix.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="sizing">How to size a sauna heater (by volume)</h2>
  <p>
    Size by cubic feet, not by the brochure's "person" count. The rule of thumb is roughly
    <strong>1 kW of heater per 45-50 cubic feet</strong> of a well-insulated room (volume = length x
    width x height). Add 15-25% for lots of glass, poor insulation, or a cold location, and about
    6 cubic feet of effective volume per square foot of glass. Then confirm against the specific
    heater's chart.
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable
    caption="Sauna room size, volume, heater kW, heat-up time, and realistic capacity (7 ft ceiling)"
    headers={["Interior", "Floor", "Volume", "Heater", "Heat-up", "Realistic capacity"]}
    rows={sizingRows}
  />

  <p>
    Note the realistic capacity column: advertised person capacity runs about a quarter to a third
    optimistic. Allow ~20 inches of bench length per seated adult, and about 70 inches if anyone
    wants to lie flat. Tiered benches let you sit higher where it is hotter.
  </p>

  <h2 id="electrical">The 240V circuit and wire gauge</h2>
  <p>
    This is the part you do not improvise. Traditional electric heaters above ~3 kW need a dedicated
    240V circuit on a GFCI breaker, installed by a licensed electrician. Use this as a planning
    reference, then confirm exact sizing with the heater's manual and your electrician (wire gauge
    also depends on run length).
  </p>

  <ComparisonTable
    caption="Approximate sauna heater circuit sizing by heater power (confirm with manual and electrician)"
    headers={["Heater power", "Voltage", "Breaker", "Wire (copper)", "Typical use"]}
    rows={circuitRows}
  />

  <Callout variant="warning" title="Electrical is not a DIY shortcut">
    <p>
      Hire a licensed electrician for any 240V heater circuit, and budget $600-$1,800 for a
      straightforward run - more if your panel needs an upgrade ($1,500-$3,000) or the run is
      trenched outdoors. A GFCI breaker is required. Wood-burning heaters skip the circuit but need a
      code-compliant chimney, heat shielding, and clearances.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="materials">Wood &amp; materials that matter</h2>
  <p>
    Wood choice is about safety and longevity, not just looks. The key rule: bench wood must stay
    cool to the touch.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Benches:</strong> aspen or abachi (lowest thermal conductivity - won't burn bare skin).</li>
    <li><strong>Walls &amp; ceiling:</strong> Western red cedar (aromatic, rot-resistant, 20-30 yr) or budget Nordic spruce.</li>
    <li><strong>Outdoor / premium:</strong> thermally modified spruce ("thermowood") for stability and weathering.</li>
    <li><strong>Never:</strong> resinous or knotty pine on bench surfaces - resin liquefies at sauna heat and burns.</li>
    <li><strong>Behind the wood:</strong> a foil vapor barrier plus insulation, and proper intake/exhaust ventilation - non-negotiable for a traditional sauna.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="heaters">A curated sauna heater shortlist</h2>
  <p>
    The heater is the single most important component in a traditional build. Rather than list dozens,
    here are eight well-regarded options worth comparing, grouped by electric, wood-burning, and
    infrared. These are starting points, not star-rated winners - size the kW to your room's volume
    and confirm against the manufacturer's chart before buying.
  </p>

  <div class="heater-grid not-prose">
    {
      heaters.map((h) => (
        <article class="heater-card">
          <div class="heater-card__head">
            <span class={`heater-card__type heater-card__type--${h.type.toLowerCase()}`}>{h.type}</span>
            <span class="heater-card__kw">{h.kw}</span>
          </div>
          <h3 class="heater-card__name">{h.name}</h3>
          <p class="heater-card__best">{h.bestFor}</p>
          <p class="heater-card__blurb">{h.blurb}</p>
          <div class="heater-card__pc">
            <div>
              <p class="heater-card__pc-h heater-card__pc-h--pro">What works</p>
              <ul>{h.pros.map((p) => <li>{p}</li>)}</ul>
            </div>
            <div>
              <p class="heater-card__pc-h heater-card__pc-h--con">What to weigh</p>
              <ul>{h.cons.map((c) => <li>{c}</li>)}</ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="heater-card__cta">
            <AffiliateButton amazonSearch={h.amazonSearch} productName={h.name} variant="primary" />
          </div>
        </article>
      ))
    }
  </div>

  <Callout variant="note" title="How to choose between them">
    <p>
      For most home builds, a well-sized <strong>electric</strong> heater from Harvia, HUUM, Finlandia,
      or EOS is the straightforward answer. Choose <strong>wood-burning</strong> only if you want
      authentic loyly or off-grid use and can build a compliant chimney. Pick <strong>infrared
      panels</strong> only if you are building an infrared room rather than a traditional one. Whatever
      you choose, match the kW to the <a href="#sizing">sizing table</a> and have a licensed
      electrician handle any 240V circuit.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 id="picks">Where to source kits, heaters &amp; materials</h2>
  <p>
    Format-level starting points, not star-rated winners. Where we mention brands, treat them as
    well-regarded examples to compare, and check spec sheets before buying.
  </p>

  <ProductCard
    id="precut-kit"
    name="Pre-cut indoor sauna kit"
    bestFor="Best for most DIY builders"
    saunaIcon="kit"
    image="/images/formats/diy-kit.webp"
    imageAlt="Stacked cedar panels, a roll of foil vapor barrier and a boxed heater for a DIY sauna kit."
    formatLabel="Pre-cut kit, seats 2-4"
    price="$3,000-$9,000 + heater"
    specs={[
      { label: "Skill", value: "Intermediate" },
      { label: "Build time", value: "1-3 days" },
      { label: "Heater", value: "Sized to room kW" },
      { label: "Electrical", value: "240V + electrician" },
    ]}
    summary={[
      "A pre-cut kit is the sweet spot for most people: pre-measured wall and bench components, vapor barrier, and a matched heater spec, assembled in a day or two. You skip the hardest cutting and fitting and still get to choose a quality heater.",
      "Superior Saunas, SaunaPlace, and Finnleo offer pre-cut kits; Almost Heaven and SaunaLife are common in the indoor space. Confirm the kit's heater kW matches your room volume.",
    ]}
    pros={[
      "Removes the most error-prone work",
      "Fast assembly; predictable result",
      "Choose your own quality heater",
    ]}
    cons={[
      "Costs more than scratch materials",
      "Less customizable than a scratch build",
      "Still needs an electrician for 240V",
    ]}
    skipIf="you want a fully custom room or the lowest possible material cost."
    amazonSearch="pre-cut sauna kit indoor"
  />

  <ProductCard
    id="heater"
    name="Traditional sauna heater (electric)"
    bestFor="Best single decision in the build"
    saunaIcon="heater"
    image="/images/formats/electric-heater.webp"
    imageAlt="A modern electric sauna heater topped with dark stones on a cedar wall."
    formatLabel="Electric heater, 4.5-9 kW"
    price="$500-$2,500"
    specs={[
      { label: "Power", value: "4.5-9 kW typical" },
